<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">Oleksandr Martyshko, Senior Mobile Software Architect at Teamwork Commerce, on why supply chain efficiency is increasingly reliant on RFID technology.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">The role of radio frequency identification (RFID) in today's supply chain is critical. Whether the goal is enhancing efficiency or mitigating losses, RFID can significantly streamline retail supply chain operations through enhanced inventory visibility.</p>

<h2>RFID-powered real-time visibility holds the supply chain together</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">Supply chain operations — inventory procurement, storage, distribution, and transportation — rely heavily on accurate inventory data. Without real-time visibility into stock, retailers can't make informed, timely decisions. If they don't know in real time which products are in high demand or sold out, they can't restock fast enough, leading to missed sales and lower customer satisfaction.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">RFID bridges that gap, enabling real-time inventory tracking as products move through the supply chain. Retailers can precisely locate their products, identify where items go missing, and act to mitigate losses. The technology also replaces manual inventory counting with automated operations — handheld RFID readers can scan products in bulk at the item level, accelerating both inventory audits and order processing. That gives retailers clearer visibility and lets staff spend more time on high-value, customer-facing work instead of manual counts.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">This also supports more sustainable supply chain practices — reducing waste, minimizing excess production, cutting emissions from unnecessary transportation and storage, and lowering the risk of unsold goods ending up in landfill.</p>

<h2>Beyond inventory tracking</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">RFID's role in inventory management is critical, but the technology offers more than tracking alone — it also provides insights for demand forecasting. Retailers can use RFID tag data to better understand purchasing trends and predict future demand with more precision, adjusting procurement strategies, identifying bottlenecks, and optimizing inventory levels ahead of time.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">Modern innovations can significantly reduce the risk of supply chain disruptions, though unexpected delays will always happen. The real-time visibility RFID provides lets retailers take proactive measures to minimize the impact of those disruptions and keep the business running. RFID has evolved from a "nice to have" into an essential part of the supply chain ecosystem, and retailers should be looking for ways to integrate it more deeply into their operations.</p>
